title: For Sale:  1955 Chinese Type 53
postcontent:
1955 Chinese Type 53 in Good Condition, small scratches on wood stock.  This gun shoots 7.62x54r that will send a fireball out the barrel and kicks like a mule....hang on.  Also has an attached bayonet that folds out.  Non-matching numbers.  Own a piece of history.

HISTORY
In the early 1950's the People's Republic of China decided there was a need to develop a carbine for issue to the People's Army. The Chinese looked to their new friends to the North, the Soviet Union, for assistance in the matter. As the doctrine of the "Human Wave" was shared by both nations, a bayonet would be an essential item on any carbine to be issued. The Soviet Union of course offered the Model 1944 Carbine as a logical solution . The Soviets were in production of the SKS at the time, but they did not want to share this new development with the Chinese. It is thought that Soviet machinery was sent to China for commencement of Type 53 production. The facts also seem to suggest this was also done in Eastern Europe as the Model 1944 Carbine production also began in Poland, Hungary, and Romania during the same time frame. The movement of the Soviet machinery allowed the Chinese to produce the Type 53 independently, which was important to both Chinese national pride and the self-sufficiency of China. This also allowed the Soviets to aid their Chinese ally without giving away a large amount of weapons technology.  Chinese production of the carbine began in 1953 and the designation of this new carbine was the Type 53 . The early proofs on the barrel shank of the Type 53 will have both Chinese characters and the number 26 or 296. The Chinese characters translate to " 53 Year Type " and the 26 or 296 are the stamping of the State Factory at Chongqing.

title: For Sale:  1915 "Coliat" Colt Army Special (Spanish Copy)
location: Santa Fe, NM, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
Yes, a "COLIAT" lol!

 This one is marked on its pressed horn grips with the trade name "Coliat". In some forums this has been translated as "Goliat' which means "goliath" in French. I don't believe that to be true. In this case, "Coliat" seems intended to fool non-English speakers into thinking they were getting a Colt. They were made by Antonio Errasti in Eibar. The revolver is intended to be a visual copy of a Colt Army Special but with S&W style lockwork. The cylinder release operates like a Colt as well.

 Errasti made these revolvers in 1917 -18 for the French army, and they were used by them in WWI - chambered in the smaller 8mm Lebel. These were already an existing design and production model for Errasti in 1917 - and it seems this one was made before that. This is because it is chambered in .38 Special. Errasti went out of business in the glut of arms that followed WWI, and with the tightening of gun control laws in Europe in that period.

 Here is why I bought this revolver in the first place: On the barrel are two great legends. The left side says ".38 SPECIAL AND US SERVICE CTGS". On top of the barrel it reads "BEST AMERICAN CARTRIDGES ARE THOSE THAT BEST FIT THE A.E. REVOLVER". Hilarious. The left side has the A.E. logo entwined to look like a S&W logo. This is the type of revolver that probably got US lawmakers to insist that foreign makers put their country of origin on their guns. There is no "Made in Spain", no "Eibar" marks, and no import marks at all on it. I find it to be an interesting piece from this time period.

 These guns were made of questionable steel and I have never fired this one, nor do I recommend it. It is a collectible and a conversation piece. if you absolutely HAVE to shoot it, I have a friend who loads about 10 grains of black powder substitute into .38 Special cases and then uses a lead bullet on top. That should be safe, or perhaps target wadcutters would also work. These guns are loose and even the crane's fitting is sloppy. If you have to shoot it, keep it light!

I think it is a neat piece of history from the WWI and before era. 

Contact me through Armslist with your number and I can arrange for you to see it here in Santa Fe. If you are too far away to come here, I can ship this to an FFL or a C&R for an additional $15.00.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 21 Skeet 20 Gauge
postcontent:
The length of the raised matted rib barrels is 28 inches. The left barrel is choked WS-2 and the right WS-1. The front sight is a Bradley red bead and the middle is the 94B Winchester white metal sight. The safety is non-automatic. The ejection is selective. Bore diameters by my CPS bore gauge are .616 for both barrels. The choke constriction on the left barrel measures just shy of .602 and the right comes in at .603 so in fact, the chokes run closer to modified. Quoting from Schwing's book on the 21 regarding chokes, it states on page 95 "Where constriction was slight, in the case of Winchester Skeet #1 and Winchester Skeet #2, choke diameter would vary with the bore."

The stock is the straight English style with the later Diamond pattern checkering on the slim beavertail forend. DAC is 1 5/8ths of an inch and DAH is 2 inches. LOP is 14 inches to the center of the checkered butt. The cast is neutral and the overall length is 44 and 5/8ths. It has "select nice wood" and a "medium comb - leaning to the thin side". Although the gold oval name plate is supposed to be engraved with the owner's initials according to the build sheet, there are no initials present. The oval is still slightly proud of the stock, so I think that he must have changed his mind about that. Weight is approximately 7 1/2 pounds.

Of course, all the provenance documents and the Cody letter go with the gun.

I'm not a dealer so be sure that your dealer will accept a shipment from a private individual. I'd ballpark shipping with insurance at $100 and any used portion of that will be refunded to the buyer via personal check. The gun will be carefully packaged and shipped in a hard case. I can go through a local dealer if needed at an additional cost to cover his transfer fee.
